{
  "texts": [
    "ArCHer presents a hierarchical framework where a Q-function is fitted using off-policy Bellman updates that runs in parallel to token-level optimization using the learned Q-function as the reward model.",
    "Critically, our approach relies on the insight that the token-level optimization is in fact a policy improvement step in disguise (Thms. 1 and 2).",
    "ArCHer uses methods like Implicit Q-Learning (IQL) Kostrikov et al. (2022) as the off-policy Bellman update since it does not require a direct implementation of the max operator.",
    "IQL uses an upper expectile to estimate max Q-values and it is not guaranteed to learn an optimal state-action value function.",
    "In contrast, our reduction mechanism demonstrates that token-level optimization is a policy improvement step, which in turn motivates our policy iteration-style algorithm."
  ]
}